quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print "I love C++":
[!raw!]
{0} << "I love C++"{1}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]New Line[/h1]

The [b]cout [/b]operator does not insert a line break at the end of the output. 
One way to print two lines is to use the [b]endl [/b]manipulator, which will put in a line break. [code format="cpp" codeId="172"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
  cout << "Hello world!" << [b]endl[/b];
  cout << "I love programming!";
  return 0;
}[/code]
The [b]endl [/b]manipulator moves down to a new line to print the second text. [img id="2398" width="100%"]

[h1]New Lines[/h1]

The new line character [b]\n[/b] can be used as an alternative to [b]endl[/b].
The backslash (\) is called an [b]escape character[/b], and indicates a "special" character.

[b]Example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="173"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
   cout << "Hello world! [b]\n[/b]";
   cout << "I love programming!";
   return 0;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2399" width="100%"]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print the words "hello" and "world" separated by a blank line:
[!raw!]
{0} << "hello {1}";
cout {2} "world";

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]New Lines[/h1]

Two newline characters placed together result in a blank line.[code format="cpp" codeId="174"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
   cout << "Hello world! [b]\n\n[/b]";
   cout << "I love programming!";
   return 0;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2400" width="100%"]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print "I love C++" with each word in a new line:
[!raw!]
cout << "I {0} love {1} C++";

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Multiple New Lines [/h1]

Using a single [b]cout [/b]statement with as many instances of  [b]\n[/b] as your program requires will print out multiple lines of text.[code format="cpp" codeId="175"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
   cout << " Hello [b]\n [/b]world! [b]\n [/b]I [b]\n [/b]love [b]\n [/b]programming!";
   return 0;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2402" width="100%"]
